var more={
  "cambodia":_c("cambodia","Cambodia",12.57,104.99,"Southeast Asia","12.5657° N, 104.9910° E",
    "A land of ancient Khmer temples, river-fed floodplains, and a resilient culture emerging from a turbulent past.",
    "Lowland / Mekong Delta","Tropical Wet/Dry","Mekong Floodplain Forest",[
      _d("angkor-wat","Angkor Wat","Siem Reap","Archaeological Wonder","angkor+wat+cambodia+temple+sunrise",
        "The world's largest religious monument, Angkor Wat is a 12th-century Khmer masterpiece of towering spires and intricate bas-reliefs.",
        "Built by King Suryavarman II, this vast temple-mountain was originally dedicated to Vishnu before becoming a Buddhist shrine. Its perfectly aligned towers reflect in the surrounding moat at dawn, creating one of the most iconic silhouettes on earth.\n\nThe temple's galleries are carved with over half a mile of narrative reliefs depicting Hindu mythology and historical battle scenes. Arriving before sunrise reveals the monument at its most ethereal, with mist still clinging to the stone.",
        {"Built":"1113–1150 AD","Style":"Khmer / Hindu-Buddhist","Size":"402 acres","UNESCO":"Listed 1992","Towers":"5 central prasat"},
        "Open daily 05:00–18:00","USD 37 (1-day pass)","13.4125° N, 103.8670° E",
        "Buy your pass the evening before to enter at the very first moment of dawn and beat the crowds."),
      _d("bayon-temple","Bayon Temple","Angkor Thom","Historic Landmark","bayon+temple+faces+cambodia",
        "The enigmatic Bayon temple rises from the heart of Angkor Thom, adorned with 216 serene stone faces gazing in every direction.",
        "Constructed in the late 12th century by King Jayavarman VII, the Bayon served as the state temple of the Khmer Empire's last great capital. Its labyrinthine corridors are lined with vivid bas-reliefs depicting naval battles, markets, and everyday Khmer life.\n\nThe tower faces — likely depicting the bodhisattva Avalokitesvara — create a surreal, meditative atmosphere unlike any other temple at Angkor. Late afternoon light turns the sandstone golden and transforms the faces into otherworldly presences.",
        {"Built":"Late 12th century","Style":"Bayon / Buddhist","Towers":"54 towers","Faces":"216 stone faces","Location":"Center of Angkor Thom"},
        "Open daily 07:30–17:30","Included in Angkor Pass","13.4413° N, 103.8593° E",
        "Climb to the upper terrace early to photograph the faces one-on-one before tour groups arrive."),
      _d("ta-prohm","Ta Prohm","Siem Reap","Jungle Ruin","ta+prohm+tree+roots+temple+cambodia",
        "Ta Prohm is the jungle-smothered temple where massive silk-cotton trees have dramatically entwined themselves with ancient stone galleries.",
        "Built in 1186 by Jayavarman VII as a Buddhist monastery and university, Ta Prohm was intentionally left unrestored to illustrate the power of nature reclaiming human-made structures. Giant Tetrameles and strangler fig trees thrust roots through walls and rooftops in a breathtaking display of organic architecture.\n\nThe temple once housed over 12,000 people and was one of the wealthiest in the Angkor complex. Today its atmospheric corridors provide one of the most photogenic and thought-provoking experiences in all of Cambodia.",
        {"Built":"1186 AD","Style":"Bayon / Buddhist","Dedicated to":"Jayavarman VII's mother","Feature":"Unrestored tree integration","UNESCO":"Listed 1992"},
        "Open daily 07:30–17:30","Included in Angkor Pass","13.4350° N, 103.8893° E",
        "Venture beyond the main photo spots into less-visited corridors for a truly solitary jungle-ruin experience."),
      _d("tonle-sap-lake","Tonle Sap Lake","Kompong Chhnang","Natural Wonder","tonle+sap+lake+floating+village+cambodia",
        "Southeast Asia's largest freshwater lake, Tonle Sap swells dramatically each monsoon season and supports an extraordinary ecosystem of floating villages.",
        "Tonle Sap's unique reverse-flow phenomenon — when the Mekong backs up into the lake each rainy season — causes its surface area to grow from 2,500 to over 16,000 square kilometers. This annual cycle sustains some of the world's most productive freshwater fisheries and the lives of hundreds of thousands of people living on its waters.\n\nThe floating villages of Kampong Phluk and Chong Khneas are fascinating communities where schools, temples, and markets all drift on the surface. Exploring by small boat at dusk, with stilted houses silhouetted against a crimson sky, is an unforgettable Cambodian experience.",
        {"Type":"Freshwater lake","Peak size":"16,000 km²","Dry season size":"2,500 km²","Fish species":"Over 200","UNESCO":"Biosphere Reserve"},
        "Boat tours daily 07:00–17:00","USD 10–20 (guided boat tour)","12.9117° N, 104.0996° E",
        "Visit between October and December when water levels are still high but boat access to the villages is easiest."),
      _d("phnom-penh-royal-palace","Royal Palace Phnom Penh","Phnom Penh","Royal Landmark","royal+palace+phnom+penh+cambodia+golden",
        "The gleaming Royal Palace of Phnom Penh is a stunning complex of Khmer-style spires and gilded pavilions that serves as the official residence of Cambodia's king.",
        "Constructed in 1866 on the banks of the Mekong-Tonle Sap confluence, the palace complex is dominated by the Throne Hall's towering 59-meter spire and the legendary Silver Pagoda with its floor of 5,000 silver tiles. The compound reflects a seamless blend of French colonial influence and traditional Khmer architecture.\n\nThe Silver Pagoda houses the sacred Emerald Buddha and a life-size gold Buddha encrusted with 9,584 diamonds. The palace grounds offer a tranquil contrast to the bustle of the capital city surrounding it.",
        {"Built":"1866 (current structures 20th c.)","Style":"Khmer / French Colonial","Highlight":"Silver Pagoda floor","Silver tiles":"5,329","Open to public":"Partial complex"},
        "Open daily 08:00–11:00, 14:00–17:00","USD 10","11.5625° N, 104.9311° E",
        "Dress modestly with covered shoulders and knees; rental sarongs are available at the gate if needed.")
    ]),
  "nepal":_c("nepal","Nepal",28.39,84.12,"South Asia","28.3949° N, 84.1240° E",
    "Home to eight of the world's ten tallest peaks, Nepal is the ultimate destination for trekkers, spiritual seekers, and lovers of living heritage.",
    "Himalayan / Terai Lowlands","Alpine / Subtropical","Himalayan Alpine Forest",[
      _d("everest-base-camp","Everest Base Camp","Solukhumbu","Mountain Expedition","everest+base+camp+himalaya+nepal+trekkers",
        "The legendary Everest Base Camp trek at 5,364 meters is the world's most iconic high-altitude pilgrimage, leading through Sherpa villages to the foot of the planet's highest summit.",
        "The 130-kilometre round-trip trek passes through the Khumbu region's rhododendron forests, high-altitude monasteries, and the dramatic Khumbu Icefall that guards the mountain's flanks. Namche Bazaar serves as the gateway hub, perched in a dramatic amphitheatre at 3,440 metres, where acclimatization days reveal sweeping views of Ama Dablam.\n\nBase Camp itself is a sprawling tent city during the spring and autumn climbing seasons, alive with the colour of expedition flags snapping in the wind. Even without attempting the summit, the trek rewards visitors with some of the most awe-inspiring mountain scenery on earth.",
        {"Altitude":"5,364 m (17,598 ft)","Best Season":"Oct–Nov, Mar–May","Duration":"12–14 days","Permit":"TIMS + Sagarmatha NP","Nearest Airport":"Lukla (Tenzing-Hillary)"},
        "Trek year-round; teahouses open Oct–May peak","USD 800–1,500 (guided, excluding flights)","27.9881° N, 86.9253° E",
        "Spend an extra acclimatization day at Namche Bazaar to dramatically reduce the risk of altitude sickness higher up."),
      _d("kathmandu-durbar-square","Kathmandu Durbar Square","Kathmandu","Historic Landmark","kathmandu+durbar+square+temples+nepal",
        "Kathmandu's Durbar Square is a UNESCO-listed open-air museum of medieval temples, courtyards, and palaces at the heart of the old capital.",
        "The square served as the ceremonial centre of the Malla and Shah dynasties for centuries, and its dense cluster of pagodas, shrines, and carved wooden windows represents the pinnacle of Newari craftsmanship. The living goddess Kumari resides in an ornate courtyard at its edge, occasionally appearing at an upper window.\n\nDespite damage from the 2015 earthquake, the square has been painstakingly restored and still pulses with daily life — vendors, pilgrims, and students sharing the ancient stones. The Taleju Temple, Jagannath Temple, and the old Royal Palace are all within steps of each other.",
        {"UNESCO":"Listed 1979","Style":"Newari / Malla Dynasty","Key site":"Kumari Ghar (Living Goddess)","Earthquake impact":"Partial damage 2015","Restored":"Ongoing since 2016"},
        "Open daily 09:00–18:00","NPR 1,000 (foreigners)","27.7042° N, 85.3074° E",
        "Arrive on a festival day like Indra Jatra to witness the square transformed into a living ceremonial spectacle."),
      _d("bhaktapur-durbar-square","Bhaktapur Durbar Square","Bhaktapur","Ancient City","bhaktapur+nepal+medieval+temples+pagoda",
        "Bhaktapur is the best-preserved of the three Kathmandu Valley royal cities, a medieval Newari town where pottery wheels still spin and peacock windows glow gold.",
        "The city's 55-Window Palace and the soaring five-tiered Nyatapola Temple — Nepal's tallest pagoda — anchor a square that has changed little in 500 years. Bhaktapur's lack of motorised traffic within the old core preserves an atmosphere of extraordinary authenticity.\n\nThe city is also famous for its rich pottery tradition in Pottery Square and for juju dhau, the creamy 'king curd' sold in clay pots. Each courtyard reveals another hidden temple, carved torana, or centuries-old water fountain still in daily use.",
        {"UNESCO":"Listed 1979","Best feature":"55-Window Palace","Tallest pagoda":"Nyatapola (5 tiers)","Specialty food":"Juju dhau (king curd)","Distance from KTM":"13 km"},
        "Open daily 07:00–19:00","USD 15 (entry fee)","27.6722° N, 85.4278° E",
        "Stay overnight in a heritage guesthouse to enjoy the square completely empty in the early morning light."),
      _d("pokhara-phewa-lake","Pokhara & Phewa Lake","Pokhara","Scenic Lakeside","pokhara+phewa+lake+reflection+annapurna+nepal",
        "Pokhara's Phewa Lake offers mirror-perfect reflections of the Annapurna massif and the iconic fishtail peak of Machapuchare from its tranquil shores.",
        "Nepal's second-largest city is the gateway to the Annapurna Circuit and Sanctuary treks, yet its lakeside promenade retains a laid-back charm ideal for rest days between adventures. The Tal Barahi Temple sits on a small island at the lake's centre, reached by colourful wooden rowboats hired along the Lakeside strip.\n\nSunrise views from the Sarangkot viewpoint above the city deliver some of the most dramatic panoramas in the Himalayas, with Dhaulagiri, Annapurna, and Machapuchare rising above a sea of clouds. The International Mountain Museum in the city is also a world-class introduction to Himalayan exploration history.",
        {"Lake area":"4.43 km²","Altitude":"827 m","Backdrop":"Annapurna Range","Best view":"Sarangkot at sunrise","Paragliding":"Launched from Sarangkot"},
        "Lake and promenade access 24 hrs; museum 09:00–17:00","Free (lakeside); USD 5 paragliding launch fee","28.2096° N, 83.9556° E",
        "Book a sunrise paragliding flight from Sarangkot for a bird's-eye view of the lake and Annapurna together."),
      _d("chitwan-national-park","Chitwan National Park","Chitwan","Wildlife Reserve","chitwan+nepal+rhino+jungle+safari",
        "Chitwan National Park is Nepal's premier wildlife sanctuary, sheltering one-horned rhinos, Bengal tigers, and gharial crocodiles in its lush Terai jungle.",
        "Established in 1973 and inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1984, Chitwan protects 952 square kilometres of dense sal forest, tall grassland, and riverine habitat. Jeep safaris and elephant-back rides through the grasslands offer reliable sightings of the greater one-horned rhinoceros, one of Asia's great conservation success stories.\n\nThe Rapti and Narayani rivers that border the park add further wildlife-watching opportunities, with gharial and marsh mugger crocodiles basking on sandy banks. Sunrise canoe trips down the Rapti River are a peaceful way to spot kingfishers, storks, and the occasional rhino drinking at the water's edge.",
        {"UNESCO":"Listed 1984","Area":"952 km²","Key species":"One-horned rhino, Bengal tiger","Best season":"Oct–Mar","Safari types":"Jeep, elephant, canoe"},
        "Park open daily 06:00–18:00","USD 25 (park entry) + USD 35 (jeep safari)","27.5291° N, 84.3542° E",
        "An early morning jeep safari into the tall elephant grass gives the highest chance of spotting tigers on the move.")
    ]),
  "sri-lanka":_c("sri-lanka","Sri Lanka",7.87,80.77,"South Asia","7.8731° N, 80.7718° E",
    "The teardrop island of the Indian Ocean blends ancient citadels, spice-scented highlands, and some of Asia's finest beaches into a compact and endlessly rewarding destination.",
    "Coastal / Highland","Tropical Monsoon","Indo-Malayan Rainforest",[
      _d("sigiriya-rock","Sigiriya Rock Fortress","Dambulla","Archaeological Wonder","sigiriya+rock+fortress+sri+lanka+sunrise",
        "Sigiriya is a 5th-century royal citadel built atop a 180-metre volcanic plug, its sheer walls adorned with exquisite frescoes of heavenly maidens.",
        "King Kashyapa I constructed this sky-palace around 477 AD, carving gardens, pools, and audience halls into the rock's base before ascending to his impregnable throne room at the summit. The famous 'Lion Staircase' — flanked by massive paws carved from the living rock — marks the final ascent through what was once a colossal lion's head gateway.\n\nAt the summit, 360-degree views sweep across the Central Province's jungle canopy to distant mountains. The sophisticated hydraulic garden system at the base, with its fountains still functional during the rainy season, reveals an astonishing level of ancient engineering.",
        {"Built":"5th century AD","Height":"180 m above surrounding plain","UNESCO":"Listed 1982","Highlight":"Mirror Wall frescoes","Climb":"1,200 steps to summit"},
        "Open daily 07:00–17:30","USD 30 (foreigners)","7.9570° N, 80.7603° E",
        "Climb on a weekday morning and reach the summit before 08:00 to avoid the midday heat and crowds."),
      _d("temple-of-the-tooth","Temple of the Tooth","Kandy","Sacred Temple","temple+of+tooth+kandy+sri+lanka+golden",
        "The Sri Dalada Maligawa in Kandy houses Buddhism's most sacred relic — a tooth of the Buddha — within a golden casket in a stunning lakeside palace complex.",
        "The relic has been venerated since the 4th century AD and its possession was historically tied to the right to rule the island. The current temple complex, situated on the shores of the Kandy Lake, was largely built in the 17th and 18th centuries under the Kandyan kings and features spectacular carved doorways and painted ceilings.\n\nThrice daily puja ceremonies fill the air with drums, flutes, and the scent of incense as worshippers offer lotus blossoms at the relic chamber. The annual Esala Perahera festival in July/August sees the tooth relic paraded through the city on a magnificently caparisoned elephant.",
        {"Relic":"Tooth of the Buddha","UNESCO":"Listed 1988 (Kandy)","Puja times":"06:30, 09:30, 18:30","Key festival":"Esala Perahera (July/Aug)","Dress code":"Covered shoulders and knees"},
        "Open daily 06:00–20:00","LKR 1,000 (foreigners)","7.2936° N, 80.6413° E",
        "Attend the evening puja at 18:30 for the most atmospheric experience with drumming and candlelight."),
      _d("nuwara-eliya-tea","Nuwara Eliya Tea Plantations","Nuwara Eliya","Tea Plantation","nuwara+eliya+tea+plantation+sri+lanka+green",
        "Nuwara Eliya's cool misty highlands are carpeted in vivid emerald tea estates producing Ceylon's most prized high-grown teas at elevations above 1,800 metres.",
        "The British transformed this cool highland bowl into a 'Little England' in the 19th century, planting tea across every hillside and building bungalows, a golf course, and a racecourse that survive to this day. The Pedro and Mackwoods Labookellie estates both offer factory tours where visitors can watch the full orthodox tea-making process from withering to rolling.\n\nThe train journey from Kandy to Nuwara Eliya through the misty hill country is consistently ranked among the world's most scenic rail routes. Women in brightly coloured saris plucking the two-leaves-and-a-bud are a quintessential image of Sri Lankan life.",
        {"Altitude":"1,868 m","Best tea":"Single-estate orange pekoe","Train route":"Kandy–Ella via Nanu Oya","Best months":"Jan–Mar (dry season)","Tours":"Pedro Estate, Labookellie"},
        "Estate tours Mon–Sat 08:00–17:00","Free (Labookellie); LKR 500 (Pedro Estate)","6.9497° N, 80.7891° E",
        "Book a window seat on the right side of the Kandy–Ella train for the best views of the tea-covered valleys."),
      _d("yala-national-park","Yala National Park","Hambantota","Wildlife Safari","yala+national+park+leopard+sri+lanka+safari",
        "Yala National Park boasts the world's highest density of wild leopards and offers thrilling jeep safaris through a dramatic mosaic of scrub jungle, lagoons, and ancient ruins.",
        "Sri Lanka's most visited national park covers 979 square kilometres of the island's southeastern dry zone, where herds of elephants share the watering holes with sloth bears, crocodiles, and countless bird species. Block 1 — the accessible tourism zone — has an extraordinary concentration of wildlife thanks to decades of protection.\n\nLeopards are regularly seen lounging in trees or patrolling their territories around the rocky outcrops near Palatupana. A licensed guide is essential for navigating the park's sandy tracks and locating the most elusive residents.",
        {"Area":"979 km² (Block 1: 141 km²)","Top predator":"Sri Lankan leopard","Elephants":"200+ in dry season","Best months":"Feb–Jul","Safaris":"Dawn and dusk 06:00–18:00"},
        "Open daily 06:00–18:00 (closed Sept–Oct for restoration)","USD 25 + USD 35 jeep hire","6.3698° N, 81.5182° E",
        "Book safaris for the 05:30 sunrise opening when leopards are most active and the light is perfect for photography."),
      _d("galle-fort","Galle Fort","Galle","Colonial Fortress","galle+fort+sri+lanka+colonial+lighthouse+ocean",
        "Galle Fort is a UNESCO-listed colonial citadel where Dutch-era ramparts encircle a living town of boutique hotels, coral-stone churches, and an iconic lighthouse above crashing Indian Ocean waves.",
        "Originally built by the Portuguese in 1588 and massively expanded by the Dutch from 1649, Galle Fort is one of the best-preserved colonial fortifications in Asia. The 36-hectare walled town contains a remarkable density of 17th and 18th-century architecture — cannon-studded bastions, a Dutch Reformed Church, and a mosque all sharing the same narrow cobblestone streets.\n\nToday the fort has reinvented itself as Sri Lanka's most sophisticated destination, with heritage boutique hotels, independent bookshops, and excellent restaurants filling its old Dutch warehouses. Walking the rampart walls at sunset, with the lighthouse glowing and the surf crashing below, is a genuinely romantic experience.",
        {"Built":"1588 (Portuguese); 1649 (Dutch)","UNESCO":"Listed 1988","Area":"36 hectares","Bastion count":"14","Lighthouse":"Built 1938, still active"},
        "Fort open 24 hrs; museums 09:00–17:00","Free (fort walls); USD 3 (Maritime Museum)","6.0281° N, 80.2167° E",
        "Stay inside the fort to experience its magical quietude after the day-trippers leave at dusk.")
    ]),
  "philippines":_c("philippines","Philippines",12.88,121.77,"Southeast Asia","12.8797° N, 121.7740° E",
    "An archipelago of 7,641 islands, the Philippines captivates with surreal limestone seascapes, ancient rice terraces, and a warm hospitality that is uniquely its own.",
    "Island Archipelago / Volcanic","Tropical Maritime","Philippine Rainforest & Coral Reefs",[
      _d("chocolate-hills","Chocolate Hills","Bohol","Natural Wonder","chocolate+hills+bohol+philippines+brown",
        "The Chocolate Hills of Bohol are over 1,200 near-perfectly conical limestone mounds that turn chocolate-brown each dry season — one of the Philippines' most surreal landscapes.",
        "Spread across 50 square kilometres of central Bohol, these geological oddities are believed to have formed through the uplift of coral deposits and subsequent erosion over millions of years. Local legend, however, credits the tears of a lovesick giant for their creation, adding a poetic dimension to the science.\n\nThe Clark Chocolate Hills Complex viewpoint provides the classic panoramic shot from a hilltop stairway, while a tarsier sanctuary nearby protects the world's smallest primates. The hills are at their most dramatic between March and May when the grass cover browns completely and the symmetry is most striking.",
        {"Count":"1,268 hills (est.)","Height":"30–50 m each","Geological age":"Millions of years","Protected area":"Yes (National Geological Monument)","Best season":"Mar–May (dry)"},
        "Viewpoint open daily 06:00–17:30","PHP 50 (viewpoint)","9.9007° N, 124.1693° E",
        "Rent a motorbike to explore the hills from ground level on quiet back roads away from the main viewpoint."),
      _d("el-nido-palawan","El Nido, Palawan","El Nido","Island Paradise","el+nido+palawan+lagoon+limestone+philippines",
        "El Nido is a breathtaking maze of towering karst limestone cliffs, hidden lagoons, and electric-turquoise waters that represent the Philippines at its most spectacular.",
        "The municipality encompasses the Bacuit Archipelago — 45 islands of dramatic karst that shelter secret lagoons, cathedral caves, and pristine coral gardens accessible only by island-hopping bangka boats. Tour A covers the celebrated Big and Small Lagoons, where cliff-walled channels open into impossibly blue chambers of glass-clear water.\n\nThe sunset view from Nacpan Beach — a sweeping four-kilometre arc of golden sand — rivals anything in Southeast Asia. El Nido is the northern gateway to the Puerto Princesa Subterranean River, a UNESCO World Heritage Site navigable by paddle boat through an underground cathedral.",
        {"Islands":"45 in Bacuit Archipelago","Top tour":"Tour A (Big & Small Lagoon)","Best beach":"Nacpan Beach","Water clarity":"Exceptional visibility 20–30 m","Best months":"Nov–Apr"},
        "Island tours daily 08:00–16:00","PHP 1,200 (Tour A, shared boat)","11.1784° N, 119.3911° E",
        "Book Tour A for sunrise departure to reach the Big Lagoon before the tour boats fill the narrow entrance channel."),
      _d("mayon-volcano","Mayon Volcano","Albay","Active Volcano","mayon+volcano+philippines+perfect+cone+eruption",
        "Mayon Volcano's near-perfect symmetrical cone rising 2,463 metres above Albay Gulf is considered the world's most perfectly shaped stratovolcano and remains one of the Philippines' most active.",
        "Mayon has erupted over 50 times in recorded history, most recently in 2023, yet its agricultural slopes remain densely settled because the volcanic soil is extraordinarily fertile. The Cagsawa Ruins — a 18th-century church buried to its belltower by an 1814 eruption — provide one of the world's most dramatic foreground subjects for the volcanic cone.\n\nATV rides through lava fields and zip-lines over cooled lava channels have made Albay a growing adventure tourism destination. The best unobstructed views of the cone are from Ligñon Hill Nature Park at dawn, when the summit often clears before clouds gather.",
        {"Height":"2,463 m","Eruptions recorded":"50+","Last eruption":"2023","Shape":"Near-perfect cone","Landmark":"Cagsawa Ruins lava burial"},
        "Viewing areas 24 hrs; Ligñon Hill 06:00–18:00","PHP 50 (Ligñon Hill)","13.2543° N, 123.6857° E",
        "Check the PHIVOLCS hazard level before visiting and never enter the 6-kilometre permanent danger zone."),
      _d("intramuros-manila","Intramuros","Manila","Colonial Fortress","intramuros+manila+philippines+colonial+fortress+walls",
        "Intramuros is Manila's 16th-century Spanish walled city, a 64-hectare sandstone citadel of cobblestone streets, baroque churches, and cannon-lined battlements rising above Manila Bay.",
        "Founded in 1571 by Miguel López de Legazpi, Intramuros was the political and religious centre of Spanish colonial power in Asia for over three centuries. Fort Santiago at its northern tip served as a prison and execution site; José Rizal, the Philippines' national hero, was imprisoned there before his martyrdom in 1896.\n\nToday the restored walls, the San Agustín Church (the oldest stone church in the country), and the Manila Cathedral form a compact district best explored by bamboo bicycle or horse-drawn calesa. The sunset view from the Baluarte de San Diego garden is one of Manila's most romantic vantage points.",
        {"Founded":"1571","UNESCO":"San Agustín Church listed 1993","Key site":"Fort Santiago","Oldest church":"San Agustín (1607)","Area":"64 hectares"},
        "Fort Santiago open daily 08:00–18:00","PHP 75 (Fort Santiago)","14.5888° N, 120.9754° E",
        "Rent a bamboo bicycle at the Intramuros Administration to cover the entire walled city in a pleasant two-hour loop."),
      _d("batad-rice-terraces","Batad Rice Terraces","Ifugao","UNESCO Terraces","batad+rice+terraces+ifugao+philippines+green",
        "The amphitheatre-shaped Batad rice terraces are among the most perfectly formed of the Ifugao Cordillera, carved by hand into the mountainside over 2,000 years ago.",
        "The Ifugao Terraces were inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1995 — a living cultural landscape where indigenous Ifugao communities continue to cultivate heirloom rice varieties using traditional muyong (private watershed forest) water management systems. Batad's bowl-like configuration, enclosed by mountains on all sides, makes it the most dramatic and photographically rewarding of the terrace clusters.\n\nThe three-hour trek from the saddle viewpoint down through the terraces to the Tappia Waterfall passes working rice fields where farmers wade knee-deep in water during the planting season. Staying in a simple family guesthouse on the terrace rim rewards visitors with fog-filled mornings of extraordinary beauty.",
        {"UNESCO":"Listed 1995","Age":"2,000+ years (est.)","Irrigation":"Traditional muyong system","Crop":"Heirloom Tinawon rice","Access":"3-hr trek from saddle"},
        "Open access 24 hrs; guided treks 07:00–15:00","PHP 50 (local guide fee)","16.8985° N, 121.0865° E",
        "Stay overnight in a terrace-rim homestay to witness the morning mist rolling through the amphitheatre at first light.")
    ]),
  "malaysia":_c("malaysia","Malaysia",4.21,108.96,"Southeast Asia","4.2105° N, 108.9758° E",
    "Malaysia's diversity of rainforest, reef, colonial heritage, and gleaming modern cities makes it one of Southeast Asia's most rewarding destinations for any style of travel.",
    "Equatorial Rainforest / Coastal","Tropical Equatorial","Sundaland Rainforest",[
      _d("petronas-twin-towers","Petronas Twin Towers","Kuala Lumpur","Modern Icon","petronas+twin+towers+kuala+lumpur+night+reflection",
        "The Petronas Twin Towers soar 452 metres above Kuala Lumpur as the world's tallest twin skyscrapers and the gleaming centrepiece of Malaysia's modern identity.",
        "Designed by César Pelli and completed in 1998, the towers draw on Islamic geometric patterns in their floor-plate design — each tower an eight-pointed star cross-section that evokes traditional Malaysian craft. The double-decker Skybridge connecting the towers at floors 41 and 42 offers vertiginous views across the city to the jungle-clad hills beyond.\n\nThe KLCC park at the towers' base features a beautifully landscaped symphony lake with nightly fountain shows synchronized to music. The basement Suria KLCC mall and the surrounding KLCC district make this a day-to-night destination in its own right.",
        {"Height":"452 m (88 floors)","Architect":"César Pelli","Completed":"1998","Skybridge":"Floors 41–42","Observation deck":"Floor 86"},
        "Skybridge/Deck: Tue–Sun 09:00–20:30","MYR 80 (Skybridge + Deck)","3.1579° N, 101.7119° E",
        "Queue for complimentary Skybridge tickets at the lower ground floor early — they sell out by mid-morning on weekends."),
      _d("mount-kinabalu","Mount Kinabalu","Sabah","Sacred Mountain","mount+kinabalu+sabah+malaysia+summit+clouds",
        "At 4,095 metres, Mount Kinabalu is the highest peak between the Himalayas and New Guinea and a UNESCO World Heritage Site of extraordinary biological richness.",
        "Kinabalu Park protects one of the world's most diverse assemblages of plant life, with over 600 orchid species, the world's largest flower (Rafflesia), and Nepenthes pitcher plants clinging to its granite slopes. The two-day summit climb via the Timpohon or Mesilau trails is the most popular trekking objective in Malaysian Borneo.\n\nSummit-day begins at 02:00 for the push to Low's Peak in time for sunrise above a sea of clouds over Borneo. The UNESCO inscription in 2000 recognised both the mountain's geological importance and its role as a sacred site for the indigenous Kadazandusun people.",
        {"Height":"4,095 m","UNESCO":"Listed 2000","Orchid species":"600+","Summit start":"02:00 (pre-dawn)","Permit":"Required, limited daily"},
        "Park gate 07:00–17:00; summit climb departs 06:30","MYR 200 (park + climb permit)","6.0750° N, 116.5577° E",
        "Book your climb permit and mountain lodge months in advance — daily summit numbers are strictly capped at 135 climbers."),
      _d("george-town-penang","George Town, Penang","Penang","UNESCO Heritage Town","george+town+penang+street+art+colonial+malaysia",
        "George Town is a UNESCO-listed living heritage city where Chinese clan houses, Hindu temples, mosques, and British colonial buildings stand side by side on streets adorned with internationally celebrated street art.",
        "Founded by Francis Light of the East India Company in 1786, George Town became one of the great entrepôt ports of the 19th century, drawing Hokkien, Hakka, Tamil, and Malay communities whose descendants still inhabit the same clan jetties and shophouses today. The 2008 UNESCO inscription with Melaka recognised the exceptional multicultural living heritage of the Straits Settlements.\n\nThe Armenian Street precinct and the clan jetties of Chew Jetty offer the most atmospheric wandering, while Penang's food scene — hawker stalls serving char kway teow, asam laksa, and cendol — is considered among the finest in Asia. The Penang Hill funicular provides cool relief and sweeping views across the strait to the mainland.",
        {"UNESCO":"Listed 2008","Founded":"1786","Heritage buildings":"5,000+ pre-war shophouses","Street art":"Ernest Zacharevic murals (2012)","Food rank":"Consistently top in Asia"},
        "Heritage zone open 24 hrs; museums vary","Free (walking); MYR 30 (Penang Hill funicular)","5.4141° N, 100.3288° E",
        "Explore the clan jetties at dawn when fishing boats return and the morning light is soft gold on the wooden walkways."),
      _d("langkawi-islands","Langkawi Islands","Kedah","Island Archipelago","langkawi+island+malaysia+turquoise+water+beach"),
      _d("langkawi-islands","Langkawi Islands","Kedah","Island Archipelago","langkawi+island+malaysia+turquoise+water+beach",
        "Langkawi is a duty-free archipelago of 99 islands rising from the Andaman Sea, celebrated for its mangrove-fringed coastlines, towering sea eagles, and the world's steepest cable car.",
        "Designated a UNESCO Global Geopark in 2007, Langkawi's geological story spans 550 million years, from the ancient Machinchang sandstone formation — the oldest in Southeast Asia — to the dramatic limestone sea stacks of the Dayang Bunting island group. The island's duty-free status makes it a popular short-break destination for regional visitors, but its beaches and wildlife remain genuinely impressive.\n\nThe Langkawi Cable Car ascends 708 metres to the summit of Gunung Machinchang, where a spectacular curved SkyBridge stretches across a ravine above the canopy. Mangrove kayaking and eagle-feeding boat tours on the Kilim River provide up-close encounters with the island's rich biodiversity.",
        {"UNESCO Geopark":"Listed 2007","Islands":"99 in archipelago","Cable car height":"708 m","Top wildlife":"White-bellied sea eagle","Duty-free":"Yes (tax-free goods)"},
        "Cable car 09:30–18:00; beaches 24 hrs","MYR 85 (cable car + SkyBridge)","6.3500° N, 99.8000° E",
        "Take a morning mangrove kayak tour before the tide drops — the channels become too shallow for easy paddling by midday."),
      _d("batu-caves","Batu Caves","Selangor","Hindu Shrine","batu+caves+malaysia+golden+statue+stairs+hindu",
        "Batu Caves is Malaysia's most iconic Hindu site, where a 43-metre golden statue of Lord Murugan guards a steep staircase of 272 rainbow-coloured steps leading into cathedral-sized limestone chambers.",
        "The caves were discovered by colonial authorities in 1878 but have been a major Hindu shrine since 1891 when a temple was established inside the Cathedral Cave by Tamil immigrants. The Sri Subramaniam Temple complex at the base is an elaborate assembly of shrines and peacock iconography dedicated to the deity Murugan.\n\nDuring the Thaipusam festival in January or February, over a million pilgrims converge on Batu Caves in one of the world's largest Hindu gatherings, with devotees carrying ornate kavadi frames pierced through their skin. The surrounding limestone hills also contain smaller caves with temples and a dark cave nature tour.",
        {"Limestone age":"400 million years","Statue height":"43 m (Lord Murugan)","Steps":"272 (rainbow-painted)","Festival":"Thaipusam (Jan/Feb)","Distance from KL":"13 km"},
        "Open daily 08:00–21:00","Free (cave entry)","3.2378° N, 101.6840° E",
        "Visit at 08:00 on a weekday to climb the steps before the midday heat and share the cathedral cave with far fewer visitors.")
    ]),
  "south-korea":_c("south-korea","South Korea",35.91,127.77,"East Asia","35.9078° N, 127.7669° E",
    "South Korea seamlessly layers a 5,000-year-old civilisation onto one of the world's most dynamic modern cultures, from palace-filled Seoul to dramatic volcanic islands and fire-coloured autumn mountains.",
    "Mountainous / Coastal Peninsula","Temperate Continental","Temperate Deciduous Forest",[
      _d("gyeongbokgung-palace","Gyeongbokgung Palace","Seoul","Royal Palace","gyeongbokgung+palace+seoul+korea+autumn+guards",
        "Gyeongbokgung is the grand northern palace of the Joseon Dynasty, its 500-year-old throne hall and reflecting ponds surrounded by the glass towers of modern Seoul in a striking contrast of eras.",
        "Built in 1395 as the principal royal palace of the newly founded Joseon Dynasty, Gyeongbokgung means 'Palace Greatly Blessed by Heaven' and once housed over 500 buildings across its 410,000-square-metre grounds. Destroyed by Japanese forces during the Imjin War (1592) and again during the colonial period, the palace has been systematically reconstructed since 1990 and now stands at roughly 40% of its original scale.\n\nThe Changing of the Royal Guard ceremony at the Heungnyemun Gate is performed twice daily in elaborate Joseon-era costumes and is one of Seoul's most photographed spectacles. The National Folk Museum and National Palace Museum both occupy the palace grounds, making this a rich full-day cultural visit.",
        {"Built":"1395 (Joseon Dynasty)","Restored":"Ongoing since 1990","Area":"410,000 m²","Guard ceremony":"10:00 and 14:00 daily","Nearby":"Bukchon Hanok Village"},
        "Open Tue–Sun 09:00–18:00 (to 21:00 summer)","KRW 3,000","37.5796° N, 126.9770° E",
        "Rent a hanbok (traditional dress) from a nearby shop for free palace entry and beautiful contrast photos against the architecture."),
      _d("jeju-island","Jeju Island","Jeju Province","Volcanic Island","jeju+island+korea+haenyo+volcanic+landscape+waterfall",
        "Jeju Island is South Korea's volcanic jewel in the Korea Strait, a UNESCO triple-crown site of lava tubes, a sacred peak, waterfalls, and the legendary women free-divers known as haenyeo.",
        "Formed by shield volcano eruptions over 1.8 million years, Jeju's 1,950-metre Hallasan is South Korea's highest peak and the centrepiece of its national park. The Manjanggul lava tube — at 13.4 kilometres the world's longest known lava tube system — winds beneath the island's eastern plain, its walls still glistening with mineral formations.\n\nThe haenyeo, elderly women who free-dive for abalone and sea urchin without breathing equipment, are a UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage and a living symbol of Jeju's matriarchal culture. Cheonjiyeon and Jeongbang waterfalls, black sand beaches, and fields of yellow canola flowers in spring complete the island's diverse appeal.",
        {"UNESCO":"World Natural Heritage 2007","Hallasan height":"1,950 m","Lava tube":"Manjanggul (13.4 km)","Haenyeo":"UNESCO Intangible Heritage 2016","Best season":"Apr (canola), Oct (foliage)"},
        "Hallasan trails 05:00–12:00 (summit); Manjanggul 09:00–18:00","KRW 1,000 (Manjanggul)","33.4890° N, 126.4983° E",
        "Hire a scooter to explore the coast road between Seongsan Ilchulbong and Udo Island at your own unhurried pace."),
      _d("bukchon-hanok-village","Bukchon Hanok Village","Seoul","Historic Village","bukchon+hanok+village+seoul+korea+traditional+rooftops",
        "Bukchon Hanok Village is a living neighbourhood of over 900 traditional Korean houses whose tiled rooftops ripple across the hillside between Gyeongbokgung and Changdeokgung palaces.",
        "Unlike open-air folk museums, Bukchon's hanok are genuine residences, studios, guesthouses, and galleries continuously inhabited for centuries on the hillside that once housed the elite families serving the Joseon court. The village's winding alleyways — particularly Gahoe-dong Street 11 — offer the most iconic view: a cascade of curved tile roofs descending toward the Seoul skyline.\n\nThe area now hosts cultural experience centres where visitors can try hanbok dressing, tea ceremony, and traditional craft workshops. Arriving at dawn on a weekday allows photography of the famous alleyway view without the crowds that gather by 09:00 on weekends.",
        {"Houses":"900+ traditional hanok","Period":"Joseon Dynasty (14th–19th c.)","Best alley":"Gahoe-dong Street 11","Residents":"Still privately inhabited","District":"Jongno-gu, Seoul"},
        "Open 24 hrs (residential area; quiet hours after 20:00)","Free","37.5826° N, 126.9850° E",
        "Visit on a foggy morning in autumn when mist settles between the rooftops and creates an atmospheric, timeless scene."),
      _d("seoraksan-national-park","Seoraksan National Park","Gangwon Province","Mountain Park","seoraksan+mountain+korea+autumn+fall+foliage+granite",
        "Seoraksan is South Korea's most dramatic mountain park, a UNESCO Biosphere Reserve of granite peaks, Buddhist temples, and Korea's most celebrated autumn foliage.",
        "The Seorak massif, rising to 1,708 metres, is the centrepiece of Gangwon Province's east coast and features some of Korea's most rugged rock climbing and multi-day ridge trekking routes. The Ulsanbawi Rock — a massive granite outcrop requiring 808 steps to reach — rewards climbers with panoramic views of the East Sea on clear days.\n\nThe Sinheungsa Temple at the park's entrance, with its giant bronze Buddha statue, serves as both a religious site and a gathering point for autumn visitors who come to see the park's maples and birches turn brilliant red and gold each October. The spring cherry blossom and winter snow seasons are equally spectacular.",
        {"UNESCO Biosphere":"Designated 1982","Peak":"Daecheongbong (1,708 m)","Best season":"Oct (foliage), Feb (snow)","Cable car":"To Gwongeumseong Fortress","Key hike":"Ulsanbawi Rock (808 steps)"},
        "Park open 24 hrs; cable car 09:00–17:00","KRW 3,500 (park entry)","38.1196° N, 128.4656° E",
        "Time your visit for the third week of October when the foliage peaks at mid-elevation trails around Heundeulbawi Rock."),
      _d("gyeongju-historic-area","Gyeongju Historic Areas","Gyeongbuk","Ancient Capital","gyeongju+korea+tumulus+burial+mounds+ancient+city",
        "Gyeongju, the ancient capital of the Silla Kingdom for nearly a millennium, is an open-air museum where royal burial mounds, Buddhist temples, and stone pagodas punctuate the cityscape at every turn.",
        "Often called 'the museum without walls,' Gyeongju served as the Silla capital from 57 BC to 935 AD and at its peak was the fourth-largest city in the world with a population of nearly one million. The Tumuli Park preserves 23 of the great royal burial mounds that once numbered over 200 across the city, and excavations have yielded extraordinary gold crowns, jade ornaments, and celadon treasures now displayed in the Gyeongju National Museum.\n\nBulguksa Temple (774 AD) and the nearby Seokguram Grotto, housing an 8th-century granite Buddha in a perfectly engineered stone rotunda, are together inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site. The Gyeongju Historic Areas (2000) encompass five heritage zones containing the most complete picture of a unified Korean kingdom in existence.",
        {"UNESCO":"Listed 2000","Kingdom":"Silla (57 BC–935 AD)","Burial mounds":"23 in Tumuli Park","Key temple":"Bulguksa (774 AD)","Museum":"Gyeongju National Museum"},
        "Tumuli Park 09:00–22:00; Bulguksa 07:00–18:00","KRW 3,000 (Tumuli Park)","35.8562° N, 129.2247° E",
        "Rent a bicycle near Tumuli Park to connect all five heritage zones efficiently — Gyeongju is one of Korea's best cycling cities.")
    ]),
  "bhutan":_c("bhutan","Bhutan",27.51,90.43,"South Asia","27.5142° N, 90.4336° E",
    "The Last Shangri-La measures its progress in Gross National Happiness, preserving an ancient Buddhist culture within pristine Himalayan valleys that have remained intentionally closed to mass tourism.",
    "High Himalayan / Valley","Alpine / Subtropical","Eastern Himalayan Broadleaf Forest",[
      _d("tigers-nest-monastery","Tiger's Nest Monastery","Paro","Sacred Monastery","tigers+nest+monastery+paro+bhutan+cliff+prayer+flags",
        "Paro Taktsang — Tiger's Nest — clings impossibly to a vertical granite cliff face 900 metres above the Paro Valley, a sacred 8th-century monastery that is the defining image of Bhutan.",
        "According to legend, Guru Rinpoche flew to this cliff on the back of a tigress and meditated in a cave here for three months, subduing the local demons and consecrating the site for Buddhism. The current monastery complex was built in 1692 and features four main temples connected by stairways carved into the living rock, draped with thousands of prayer flags.\n\nThe three-hour hike ascends through blue pine and rhododendron forest, with a stunning viewpoint where the monastery hangs across a ravine accessible by a chain-bridge. Monks still meditate in the sacred caves below the main temple, maintaining an unbroken spiritual lineage that stretches back 13 centuries.",
        {"Altitude":"3,120 m (monastery)","Hike":"3 hrs one way","Founded":"1692 (current buildings)","Legend":"Guru Rinpoche, 8th century","Best light":"Morning (east-facing cliff)"},
        "Open daily 08:00–13:00, 14:00–17:00","Nu 500 (entry, included in BTF)","27.4914° N, 89.3639° E",
        "Begin hiking by 07:00 to arrive in clear conditions before afternoon clouds build around the cliff face."),
      _d("punakha-dzong","Punakha Dzong","Punakha","Fortress Monastery","punakha+dzong+bhutan+monastery+river+fortress+white",
        "Punakha Dzong is the most beautiful of Bhutan's fortress monasteries, a gleaming white palace at the confluence of the Mo and Pho Chhu rivers, framed by jacaranda trees in spring bloom.",
        "Built in 1637 by Zhabdrung Ngawang Namgyal — the unifier of Bhutan — Punakha Dzong served as the country's capital and seat of government for over 300 years and still hosts the Central Monastic Body each winter. The interior courtyards feature remarkable woodcarving, and the main assembly hall's golden Buddha statues and painted silk thangkas are among the finest in Bhutan.\n\nThe spring festival of Punakha Tshechu brings the dzong to life with mask dances and the unfurling of a giant silk thangka. The surrounding valley of rice paddies and chilli fields backed by snow-capped peaks is one of the most picturesque agricultural landscapes in the Himalayas.",
        {"Built":"1637","Valley altitude":"1,200 m (Bhutan's lowest dzong)","Rivers":"Mo Chhu and Pho Chhu confluence","Festival":"Punakha Tshechu (Feb/Mar)","Winter residence":"Central Monastic Body"},
        "Open daily 09:00–17:00 (monks permitting)","Included in Bhutan Tourist Fee","27.5973° N, 89.8636° E",
        "Visit in late February during Punakha Tshechu when the jacaranda trees are in full purple bloom around the dzong."),
      _d("dochula-pass","Dochula Pass","Thimphu","Mountain Pass","dochula+pass+bhutan+chortens+himalaya+mist+prayer+flags",
        "Dochula Pass at 3,100 metres offers one of the most dramatic panoramas in Bhutan — 108 memorial chortens rising through pine mist with the entire eastern Himalayan range stretching across the horizon on clear days.",
        "The 108 Druk Wangyal chortens were built by the Queen Mother Ashi Dorji Wangmo Wangchuck in honour of Bhutanese soldiers killed in a 2003 military operation, and their symmetrical grouping on the windswept pass has become one of Bhutan's most photographed scenes. The Druk Wangyal Temple nearby was inaugurated in 2008 to celebrate the centenary of the Wangchuck dynasty.\n\nThe pass is located just an hour's drive east of Thimphu and is frequently combined with a visit to Punakha. On winter mornings after a fresh snowfall, the chortens appear to float above a sea of clouds with the Himalayan giants — including Gangkhar Puensum, the world's highest unclimbed peak — visible behind them.",
        {"Altitude":"3,100 m","Chortens":"108 Druk Wangyal","Built":"2004–2005","View":"Eastern Himalayan panorama","Best condition":"Dec–Feb (clear days)"},
        "Open 24 hrs","Free (public pass)","27.4818° N, 89.7319° E",
        "Stop here on the way to Punakha on a clear winter morning for the best chance of seeing the full Himalayan panorama."),
      _d("paro-valley","Paro Valley","Paro","Scenic Valley","paro+valley+bhutan+green+rice+fields+farmhouse+himalaya",
        "The Paro Valley is Bhutan's most storied and photogenic valley, a gentle bowl of rice paddies, apple orchards, ancient temples, and white-washed farmhouses watched over by the ruined Drukgyel Dzong.",
        "Paro is home to Bhutan's only international airport, threading the narrow valley floor in one of the world's most challenging approach paths, and serves as the gateway for most visitors entering the country. Beyond Tiger's Nest, the valley contains Kyichu Lhakhang — one of Bhutan's oldest temples, built in 659 AD by Tibetan king Songtsen Gampo — and the National Museum of Bhutan housed in a striking Ta Dzong watchtower.\n\nThe valley's autumn harvest transforms the terraced fields to gold, while spring brings rhododendron and apple blossom to the hillsides. Walking or cycling the valley floor between farmhouses, suspension bridges, and prayer flag-strung hilltops is among the most peaceful rural experiences in the Himalayan region.",
        {"Valley altitude":"2,200 m","Oldest temple":"Kyichu Lhakhang (659 AD)","Museum":"Ta Dzong (National Museum)","Airport":"Paro Int'l (world's most challenging)","Best season":"Mar–May, Sep–Nov"},
        "Valley 24 hrs; Kyichu Lhakhang 08:00–17:00","Nu 300 (National Museum)","27.4281° N, 89.4105° E",
        "Cycle the valley floor between Paro town and Drukgyel Dzong in the late afternoon when the light turns the farmhouses amber."),
      _d("thimphu-tashichho-dzong","Tashichho Dzong","Thimphu","Royal Fortress","thimphu+tashichho+dzong+bhutan+fortress+river+monks",
        "Tashichho Dzong is the seat of the Bhutanese government and the King's throne room, a magnificent whitewashed fortress on the banks of the Wang Chhu river at the heart of Thimphu.",
        "Originally built in 1641 and massively rebuilt in 1962 under the third King using traditional construction techniques — without nails and without architectural blueprints — the dzong is a masterpiece of Bhutanese vernacular architecture. Its golden roofs, whitewashed walls, and crimson-robed monks crossing the courtyard represent the most quintessential image of the country's theocratic culture.\n\nThe dzong is particularly magnificent during the Thimphu Tshechu festival in September or October, when its courtyard becomes the stage for the kingdom's largest religious masked-dance festival. Visitors may enter the courtyards on weekday mornings before government offices open.",
        {"Built":"1641 (rebuilt 1962)","Function":"Government HQ + summer monastic body","Festival":"Thimphu Tshechu (Sep/Oct)","River":"Wang Chhu","Construction":"Traditional, no nails"},
        "Open weekdays 17:00–19:00; weekends 10:00–17:00","Free","27.4750° N, 89.6370° E",
        "Attend the Thimphu Tshechu festival to see the dzong's courtyard filled with masked cham dances and hundreds of pilgrims in their finest kira and gho.")
    ]),
  "myanmar":_c("myanmar","Myanmar",21.92,95.96,"Southeast Asia","21.9162° N, 95.9560° E",
    "Myanmar's ancient pagoda plains, rose-tinted lakes, and golden-spired cities preserve one of Southeast Asia's most extraordinary and least-altered Buddhist cultures.",
    "Mountainous / River Delta","Tropical Monsoon","Irrawaddy Moist Forest",[
      _d("bagan-temples","Bagan Temples","Mandalay Region","Archaeological Zone","bagan+temples+myanmar+sunrise+hot+air+balloon+pagodas",
        "Bagan is one of Asia's greatest archaeological landscapes — over 3,500 Buddhist temples, pagodas, and monasteries scattered across 42 square kilometres of the dusty Irrawaddy plain.",
        "Built primarily between the 11th and 13th centuries under the Bagan Kingdom, this concentration of religious monuments rivals Angkor and the Roman Forum as one of humanity's most extraordinary architectural achievements. The plain's three major temple complexes — Ananda, Dhammayangyi, and Thatbyinnyu — each represent a different stylistic peak of Bagan's building programme.\n\nHot-air balloon flights at sunrise over the temple plain remain one of the bucket-list experiences of Southeast Asia, with thousands of spires emerging from the mist below. E-bike rental is the ideal ground-level exploration method, allowing access to remote temples that tour groups never reach.",
        {"Temples":"3,500+ (2,000 original)","Period":"11th–13th century","Area":"42 km²","UNESCO":"Applied (political situation pending)","Best transport":"E-bike"},
        "Sites open daily 05:00–20:00","USD 20 (archaeological zone pass)","21.1717° N, 94.8585° E",
        "Rent an e-bike the evening before and plan a self-guided route to remote temples far from the sunrise crowds."),
      _d("inle-lake","Inle Lake","Shan State","Floating Village Lake","inle+lake+myanmar+leg+rowing+fisherman+golden+sunset",
        "Inle Lake is a serene highland lake in the Shan Plateau where Intha fishermen balance on one leg to row, villages float on woven reed islands, and the water turns molten gold at dusk.",
        "At 900 metres above sea level in the Shan Hills, Inle covers 116 square kilometres and hosts the unique Intha people — 'the sons of the lake' — who have developed an ingenious floating garden agriculture system by piling up water hyacinth and silt to create cultivated islands. The five-day rotating market that circles the lake's village circuit is one of Myanmar's most vibrant and authentic markets.\n\nThe Phaung Daw Oo Pagoda, housing five ancient golden Buddha images, is the lake's most sacred site and the focus of an extraordinary annual festival where the images are ferried around the lake on a royal barge rowed by hundreds of leg-rowers. Sunrise on the water, with egrets fishing through the mist and long-tail boats weaving through reed channels, is deeply tranquil.",
        {"Altitude":"900 m","Size":"116 km²","People":"Intha (leg rowers)","Agriculture":"Floating gardens","Market":"5-day rotating circuit"},
        "Boat tours daily 06:00–17:00","USD 3 (entry fee) + USD 15–25 (full-day boat)","20.5151° N, 96.9007° E",
        "Hire a boat for a full day and ask your boatman to include the Maing Thauk market whichever day falls in the five-day rotation."),
      _d("shwedagon-pagoda","Shwedagon Pagoda","Yangon","Sacred Pagoda","shwedagon+pagoda+yangon+myanmar+golden+twilight",
        "Shwedagon is Myanmar's most sacred Buddhist site, a 99-metre solid gold stupa enshrined with 5,000 diamonds and 2,000 rubies that has drawn pilgrims for over 2,500 years.",
        "According to tradition, the Shwedagon enshrines eight hairs of the Gautama Buddha along with relics of three previous Buddhas, making it the most spiritually significant pagoda in the Theravada Buddhist world. The main stupa is surrounded by a constellation of smaller shrines, bells, and prayer pavilions on a hilltop terrace approached by four grand stairways from the cardinal directions.\n\nThe pagoda's 60,000-gold-leaf-covered tip is encrusted with 4,531 diamonds, including a 76-carat diamond at the very apex. Evening is the most magical time to visit, when the setting sun causes the stupa to glow incandescent gold and the faithful circumambulate barefoot on warm marble.",
        {"Height":"98 m","Gold leaf":"60,000+ sheets","Diamonds":"4,531 (76-carat at apex)","Age":"2,500+ years (traditional)","Location":"Singuttara Hill, Yangon"},
        "Open daily 04:00–22:00","USD 10","16.7984° N, 96.1496° E",
        "Remove shoes and socks at the covered stairways as required, and visit barefoot in the early evening for the warmest marble underfoot."),
      _d("mandalay-hill","Mandalay Hill","Mandalay","Sacred Hill","mandalay+hill+myanmar+sunset+pagoda+monks+view",
        "Mandalay Hill is a 240-metre sacred promontory crowned with gilded pagodas that commands sweeping views over the royal city, the Irrawaddy River, and the distant Shan Hills.",
        "The hill is prophesied in Buddhist tradition as a site the Buddha himself visited and blessed, and the covered walkway spiralling to its summit passes dozens of shrines, gilded Buddhas, and the stories of Myanmar's cosmological mythology rendered in painted dioramas. A large standing Buddha near the summit points his finger toward the city below — fulfilling the legend that a great city would arise in that direction.\n\nThe summit's Sutaungpyei Pagoda is surrounded by meditation halls and souvenir sellers, but the real reward is the 360-degree view at sunset when Mandalay Palace's moat glints in the dying light and the pagoda spires turn copper. The covered walkway from the southern entrance protects visitors from rain and sun during the long ascent on bare feet.",
        {"Height":"240 m","Ascent":"Covered walkway (steep but shaded)","Top temple":"Sutaungpyei Pagoda","View":"Mandalay Palace + Irrawaddy","Best time":"Sunset"},
        "Open daily 05:00–21:00","Free","21.9960° N, 96.0869° E",
        "Begin the covered walkway climb 90 minutes before sunset to reach the summit terrace with time to find the best viewpoint."),
      _d("hpa-an-karst","Hpa-An Karst Landscape","Kayin State","Limestone Landscape","hpa+an+myanmar+limestone+karst+cave+lake+reflection",
        "The Hpa-An valley is a dreamlike landscape of soaring limestone karst towers reflected in flat paddy fields, with sacred caves sheltering thousands of Buddha images above serene green rivers.",
        "The Saddan Cave near Hpa-An is one of Myanmar's most impressive, a cathedral-sized cavern whose exit opens onto a tranquil lake traversed by rowing boats through lily pads with karst mountains rising on all sides. The nearby Kawgun Cave features hundreds of tiny Buddha figures pressed into the cave walls, a 7th-century creation of extraordinary delicacy.\n\nMount Zwegabin, a dramatic 722-metre karst pinnacle, can be climbed in 2–3 hours to a summit monastery with panoramic views of the entire valley and the Thai border hills beyond. Cycling between caves, rice paddies, and wooden monasteries on empty rural roads is one of Myanmar's most underrated travel experiences.",
        {"Region":"Kayin (Karen) State","Main cave":"Saddan Cave (bat colony at dusk)","Key peak":"Mount Zwegabin (722 m)","Distance from Yangon":"7 hrs by bus","Cycling":"Best explored by bicycle"},
        "Caves open daily 07:00–17:00","MMK 3,000 per cave site","16.8879° N, 97.6316° E",
        "Time a visit to Saddan Cave for dusk when millions of bats pour from the cave exit in a swirling column visible for kilometres.")
    ]),
  "jordan":_c("jordan","Jordan",30.59,36.24,"Middle East","30.5852° N, 36.2384° E",
    "Jordan is an ancient crossroads of civilisations where rose-red Nabataean cities, Roman colonnade streets, and vast desert wildernesses converge in one compact and welcoming kingdom.",
    "Desert / Highland","Mediterranean / Arid","Arabian Desert Steppe",[
      _d("petra-treasury","Petra — The Treasury","Ma'an Governorate","Rock-Cut City","petra+treasury+jordan+rose+red+rock+carved+ancient",
        "Al-Khazneh — the Treasury — is the iconic rose-red rock-carved facade of the ancient Nabataean city of Petra, revealed in a gasp at the end of the narrow Siq canyon.",
        "The Nabataeans carved Petra from the sandstone cliffs of southern Jordan between the 4th century BC and the 2nd century AD, creating a city of over 800 rock-cut tombs, temples, and public buildings that served as the capital of a spice-trade empire. The 1.2-kilometre Siq gorge, barely two metres wide in places, builds extraordinary anticipation before the Treasury's 40-metre facade bursts into view.\n\nBeyond the Treasury, the Rose City extends into a vast ancient urban landscape with a Roman-style colonnaded street, a theatre carved for 8,500 spectators, and the Monastery — a structure even larger than the Treasury accessible by 800 steep steps. Petra by Night, held three times weekly, transforms the Siq into a candlelit procession to the Treasury under a canopy of stars.",
        {"Founded":"4th century BC","Culture":"Nabataean Kingdom","UNESCO":"Listed 1985","Siq length":"1.2 km","Facade height":"40 m (Treasury)"},
        "Open daily 06:00–18:00 (winter) / 06:00–19:00 (summer)","JOD 50 (1-day); JOD 55 (2-day)","30.3285° N, 35.4444° E",
        "Arrive at opening time (06:00) to walk the Siq in golden morning light completely alone before the day-trippers arrive."),
      _d("wadi-rum-desert","Wadi Rum Desert","Aqaba Governorate","Desert Wilderness","wadi+rum+jordan+red+desert+rock+formations+camel",
        "Wadi Rum is a spectacular protected wilderness of towering red sandstone mountains, wind-sculpted rock bridges, and vast sand plains that served as T.E. Lawrence's wartime base and a stand-in for Mars in countless films.",
        "The Valley of the Moon — as Wadi Rum translates — covers 720 square kilometres of UNESCO-protected desert landscape where Bedouin tribes have lived for thousands of years and where Nabataean and Thamudic inscriptions cover many rock faces. Jeep tours, camel rides, and multi-day trekking routes thread between iconic formations including Jebel Khazali, Lawrence's Spring, and the Burdah Rock Bridge.\n\nSleeping in a Bedouin desert camp under Wadi Rum's extraordinary night sky — among the clearest in the Middle East — is an essential experience. The red landscape shifts from pale ochre at noon to deep crimson, violet, and shadow as the sun sets behind the western escarpment.",
        {"UNESCO":"Listed 2011","Area":"720 km²","Max elevation":"Jebel Rum (1,754 m)","Film sets":"The Martian, Lawrence of Arabia","Bedouin camps":"Traditional goat-hair tents"},
        "Open 24 hrs (visitor centre 08:00–17:00)","JOD 5 (entry) + JOD 25–40 (jeep tour)","29.5832° N, 35.4200° E",
        "Book an overnight stay at a Bedouin camp to see the Milky Way arch over the desert after the day-trippers leave."),
      _d("dead-sea-jordan","Dead Sea, Jordan","Amman Governorate","Salt Lake","dead+sea+jordan+floating+mineral+salt+sunset",
        "The Dead Sea — at 430 metres below sea level the lowest point on earth — is a hypersaline lake where the intense buoyancy allows effortless floating in mineral-rich water against a backdrop of the Judean Hills.",
        "Fed primarily by the Jordan River, the Dead Sea has a salinity of approximately 34% — nearly ten times that of the ocean — creating an environment inhospitable to all but a few extremophile microorganisms. The mineral-rich black mud drawn from the sea floor is prized globally for its therapeutic and cosmetic properties and is applied at the lake's beach resorts.\n\nThe Jordanian eastern shore offers resort beaches with private beach clubs and less infrastructure than the Israeli western shore, providing a more atmospheric and affordable experience. Sunset over the sea, with the Judean Hills turning purple on the far shore, is one of the most otherworldly spectacles in the Middle East.",
        {"Elevation":"-430 m (lowest on Earth)","Salinity":"~34%","Length":"50 km","Width":"15 km","Therapeutic":"Mineral mud + high UV blockage"},
        "Beach resorts open daily 08:00–18:00","JOD 15–25 (resort beach access)","31.5590° N, 35.4732° E",
        "Apply the black mineral mud generously, wait for it to dry completely, and rinse in the sea for maximum skin benefit."),
      _d("jerash-roman-city","Jerash Roman City","Jerash","Roman Ruins","jerash+jordan+roman+ruins+columns+colonnaded+street",
        "Jerash is one of the best-preserved Roman provincial cities in the world, a largely unexcavated urban landscape of colonnaded streets, oval forums, and hillside theatres where chariot races are re-enacted daily.",
        "Known in antiquity as Gerasa, Jerash was a wealthy city of the Decapolis league and reached its architectural peak in the 2nd and 3rd centuries AD when its streets were lined with marble and its temples rivalled those of Rome. The 90-metre-diameter Oval Plaza — unique in the Roman world for its elliptical colonnade — is the breathtaking entry point into the archaeological zone.\n\nThe chariot racing demonstrations in the Hippodrome and the Roman Army and Chariot Experience (RACE) daily show bring the city vividly to life for visitors. The South Theatre, with 3,000 seats still intact, regularly hosts the Jerash Festival of Culture and Arts each summer.",
        {"Founded":"Hellenistic, expanded 1st–3rd c. AD","UNESCO":"Not yet listed (applied)","Highlight":"Oval Plaza colonnade","South Theatre":"3,000-seat capacity","Distance from Amman":"48 km north"},
        "Open daily 08:00–18:00 (summer) / 08:00–16:00 (winter)","JOD 10","32.2750° N, 35.8922° E",
        "Arrive for the 11:00 RACE chariot show at the Hippodrome and combine it with a leisurely lunch at the site's shaded café."),
      _d("wadi-mujib-reserve","Wadi Mujib Nature Reserve","Madaba","Nature Reserve","wadi+mujib+jordan+canyon+river+gorge+trekking+water",
        "Wadi Mujib is Jordan's 'Grand Canyon' — a dramatic gorge where the Mujib River carves through towering red sandstone cliffs before emptying into the Dead Sea, offering one of the Middle East's most thrilling canyon treks.",
        "The reserve drops from an elevation of 900 metres in the Moab highlands to the Dead Sea at -400 metres, creating a remarkable biodiversity gradient that supports over 300 bird species and rare carnivores including the Nubian Ibex and striped hyena. The Siq Trail — the reserve's most popular route — requires wading and swimming through the river gorge for 2.5 kilometres between sheer red walls that in places narrow to a few metres.\n\nRSPN (Royal Society for the Protection of Nature) manages the reserve and operates eco-lodges along the Dead Sea shoreline as base camps for the canyon trails. The contrast of swimming through cool canyon water with the hot desert sun directly above is a genuinely exhilarating experience.",
        {"Elevation range":"-400 m to +900 m","UNESCO Ramsar":"Wetland site","Siq Trail":"2.5 km (wading required)","Bird species":"300+","Best months":"Apr–Oct"},
        "Reserve open daily 08:00–17:00 (Apr–Oct only)","JOD 21 (Siq Trail, includes life jacket)","31.4667° N, 35.6333° E",
        "Wear water shoes with grip and a dry bag for your valuables — the gorge floor is slippery and deeper pools require swimming.")
    ]),
  "uae":_c("uae","UAE",23.42,53.85,"Middle East","23.4241° N, 53.8478° E",
    "The United Arab Emirates has transformed desert into spectacle, raising the world's tallest towers and grandest mosques from the sands while preserving the pearl-diving and falconry traditions of its Bedouin past.",
    "Desert / Coastal","Hot Desert","Arabian Desert & Coastal Mangrove",[
      _d("burj-khalifa","Burj Khalifa","Dubai","Modern Icon","burj+khalifa+dubai+skyscraper+night+lights+fountain",
        "The Burj Khalifa pierces the sky at 828 metres as the world's tallest structure, its needle-like form dominating the Dubai skyline and dwarfing the dancing Dubai Fountain below.",
        "Designed by Adrian Smith of Skidmore, Owings & Merrill and completed in 2010, the tower draws on the geometry of the Hymenocallis desert flower and the spiralling forms of Islamic architecture to create its tapering, buttressed form. At its base, the 30-acre Burj Khalifa Lake hosts the Dubai Fountain — the world's largest choreographed fountain system — that performs to music every evening on the half-hour.\n\nThe At The Top observation decks on floors 124, 125, and 148 offer views extending over 95 kilometres on clear days across the Arabian Gulf and the desert interior. The tower contains a hotel, residences, offices, and corporate suites stacked across 163 floors served by the world's fastest double-deck elevators.",
        {"Height":"828 m (163 floors)","Architect":"Adrian Smith, SOM","Completed":"2010","Observation deck":"Floor 124/125 + 148 (SKY)","Fountain":"Dubai Fountain (world's largest)"},
        "Observation deck daily 08:00–23:00","AED 149 (floor 124); AED 379 (SKY level 148)","25.1972° N, 55.2744° E",
        "Book the SKY observation deck (floor 148) tickets online weeks ahead and time your visit for the 19:30 Dubai Fountain show visible from above."),
      _d("sheikh-zayed-mosque","Sheikh Zayed Grand Mosque","Abu Dhabi","Grand Mosque","sheikh+zayed+mosque+abu+dhabi+white+domes+reflection",
        "The Sheikh Zayed Grand Mosque is one of the world's largest mosques and a masterpiece of white marble architecture whose 82 domes and 1,000 columns are perfectly mirrored in surrounding reflection pools.",
        "Completed in 2007 and housing up to 40,000 worshippers, the mosque was commissioned by the UAE's founder Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan as a symbol of Islamic architectural achievement that drew craftsmen and materials from 38 countries. The main prayer hall's carpet — woven by 1,200 Iranian artisans — is the world's largest hand-knotted carpet, covering 5,627 square metres.\n\nThe mosque's exterior glows white at midday and shifts through pearl, rose, and lavender tones as the sun moves, while at night the floodlit domes produce a blue-white luminescence that is reflected to infinity in the pools. Non-Muslim visitors are welcome outside prayer times and abaya robes are provided free of charge at the entrance.",
        {"Completed":"2007","Capacity":"40,000 worshippers","Columns":"1,096 (marble-clad)","Carpet":"World's largest (5,627 m²)","Chandelier":"World's largest (12 m diameter)"},
        "Open Sat–Thu 09:00–22:00, Fri 14:00–22:00","Free","24.4128° N, 54.4749° E",
        "Visit on a Thursday evening when the white marble is dramatically floodlit and the reflection pools glow with colour."),
      _d("palm-jumeirah","Palm Jumeirah","Dubai","Artificial Island","palm+jumeirah+dubai+aerial+luxury+ocean+island",
        "Palm Jumeirah is the world's largest artificial island, a palm-tree-shaped archipelago of luxury residences and hotels that extended Dubai's coastline by 78 kilometres into the Arabian Gulf.",
        "Constructed between 2001 and 2006 using 94 million cubic metres of rock and sand dredged from the Gulf, Palm Jumeirah added 16 fronds and a crescent-shaped outer breakwater to create over 100 kilometres of new beachfront. The Atlantis The Palm resort at the crescent's crown became its defining landmark when it opened in 2008, followed by the ultra-luxury Atlantis The Royal in 2023.\n\nThe Palm Monorail connects the mainland to the Atlantis Hotel, while the Nakheel Mall at the trunk hub and the beach clubs along the fronds give the island a self-contained resort atmosphere. The Palm Tower's observation deck on floor 52 provides an aerial view of the palm's geometry from above, most clearly visible from the air or from the skyscraper observation decks on the mainland.",
        {"Constructed":"2001–2006","Fronds":"16 residential fronds + crescent","Coastline added":"78 km","Sand volume":"94 million m³","Landmark hotel":"Atlantis The Palm (2008)"},
        "Palm Monorail daily 09:00–22:00; beach clubs vary","AED 20 (monorail); beach clubs AED 100–300","25.1124° N, 55.1390° E",
        "Take the Palm Monorail to the Atlantis end at sunset and walk back along the crescent breakwater for unobstructed Dubai skyline views."),
      _d("dubai-old-souk","Dubai Old Souk","Dubai","Historic Market","dubai+old+souk+gold+spices+traditional+market+abra",
        "Dubai's interlocking Gold and Spice souks on the banks of the Dubai Creek preserve the city's 19th-century trading soul, where saffron mountains and 10-tonne daily gold turnover fill the ancient arcade lanes.",
        "The narrow covered alleys of the Deira spice souk perfume the air with frankincense, dried rose petals, and the earthy tang of myrrh — trade goods carried on the same dhow routes plied today by wooden boats moored along the Creek. The adjacent Gold Souk's 380 retailers display an estimated 10 tonnes of gold jewellery daily, making it the world's largest gold market by some measures.\n\nCrossing the Creek by abra — a traditional wooden water taxi costing AED 1 — connects the Deira souks to the Bur Dubai Textile Souk, completing a full loop through Dubai's living mercantile heritage. The alleyways after dark, lit by gold-case display windows and the scent of oud incense, are one of Dubai's most atmospheric and most affordable experiences.",
        {"Creek":"Dubai Creek (historic trading channel)","Gold Souk":"380 retailers, ~10 t gold daily","Spice Souk":"Traditional Deira market","Abra fare":"AED 1 (water taxi)","Best time":"Evening (after 18:00)"},
        "Souks daily 10:00–22:00 (Fri 14:00–22:00)","Free (entry); AED 1 (abra)","25.2675° N, 55.2998° E",
        "Ride the abra across the Creek at dusk when the water reflects the souk lights and traditional dhows glide past wooden abras."),
      _d("liwa-oasis","Liwa Oasis","Abu Dhabi","Desert Oasis","liwa+oasis+abu+dhabi+massive+sand+dunes+desert+camp",
        "Liwa Oasis sits at the edge of the Rub' al Khali — the world's largest continuous sand desert — where some of the planet's tallest sand dunes rise over 300 metres from a lush date-palm oasis.",
        "The ancestral homeland of the ruling Al Nahyan family, Liwa is a 150-kilometre crescent of date palm plantations in the Abu Dhabi interior, fringed by the vast orange dune seas of the Empty Quarter. The Moreeb Dune — nicknamed 'the scary mountain' — rises at a 50-degree incline to approximately 300 metres and is the site of the annual Liwa International Festival's dune-driving championship.\n\nOvernight desert camps at the base of the great dunes offer stargazing of extraordinary clarity, far from any light pollution, with the Milky Way a vivid band overhead. Camel treks, sandboarding, and morning dune walks in the cool golden light are the essential Liwa activities for visitors escaping the Gulf's coastal cities.",
        {"Location":"Edge of Rub' al Khali (Empty Quarter)","Dune height":"Up to 300+ m (Moreeb Dune)","Length of oasis":"~150 km crescent","Distance from Abu Dhabi":"250 km south","Date palms":"Millions across the oasis"},
        "Open 24 hrs (desert access); camps by booking","AED 300–600 (overnight desert camp)","23.1167° N, 53.7500° E",
        "Book a fly-in by light aircraft from Abu Dhabi to appreciate the scale of the dune sea before landing on the desert airstrip.")
    ])
};
